<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-610-419  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 610 419.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 19 1990 v7 n46 p55(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>3Com unveils intelligent hubs for Ethernet LANs. (3Com Corp.andO;introduces LinkBuilder network hubs) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sullivan, Kristina B.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>3Com Corp introduces LinkBuilder, a new line of Ethernet hubs andassociated modules that provide connections for various types ofwiring.andP;  The new concentrators are based on SynOpticsCommunications Inc's LattisNet 3000 architecture and comply withthe new 10BaseT standard for unshielded twisted-pair LANs.andP;  The$1,995 LinkBuilder 100 is a four-slot hub for linking up to 33users; the 12-port LinkBuilder 500 supports up to 132 users andcosts $4,450.andP;  Either hub can use 3Com's new line of distributionmodules ranging from a $1,795 eight-port thin coaxial connector toa $6,295 fiber-optic network management module.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   3Com Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    COMS.andO;Product:   3Com LinkBuilder 100 (Network hub) (Product introduction)3Com LinkBuilder 500 (Network hub) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Network HubsEthernetProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Kristina B. SullivanandM;LAS VEGAS--Expanding its product line to provide its network customers withmore of a one-stop shopping solution, 3Com Corp. last week announced itsfirst intelligent Ethernet hubs.andM;The $419 million networking firm unveiled at Comdex/Fall here two Ethernetconcentrators and a bevy of associated modules that provide unshieldedtwisted-pair, thin coaxial and fiber-optic wiring connections.andM;The new LinkBuilder hubs are based on SynOptics Communications Inc.'sLattisNet System 3000 architecture and can operate with any 10BaseT-compliantproducts, according to Anthony Spielman, a product manager at 3Com's NetworkAdapter Division in Santa Clara, Calif.andP;  The new concentrators are part of3Com's Open Management Architecture platform for enterprisewide networking,he said.andM;&quot;3Com's role is evolving to be more and more the supplier of products forlots of multivendor needs,&quot; said Craig Burton, CEO of Clarke Burton Corp., aconsulting firm in Salt Lake City.andP;  &quot;Before, the notion of buying adaptersfrom one group and hubs from another was bothersome to some people.&quot;andM;The LinkBuilder 100 is a four-slot hub intended for work groups with up to 33users.andP;  One slot is reserved for a network-management or retiming modulewhile the other three can be used with 10BaseT, thin-coaxial or fiber-opticmodules.andP;  LinkBuilder 100 is priced at $1,995.andM;Larger work groups can be connected with the LinkBuilder 500, a 12-port hubwith 11 ports reserved for the same networking modules as for the smallerhub, and one for retiming or network-management modules.andP;  As many as 132users can be joined to the $4,450 LinkBuilder 500.andM;Distribution modules used in either hub include a $3,350, 12-port 10BaseTmodule; a $1,795, eight-port thin-coax module; and a $2,895, six-channelfiber-optic module.andP;  The network-management module is available in a $5,895thin coax or $6,295 fiber-optic version.andP;  Retiming modules are priced at$1,495 for thin coax and $1,895 for fiber optic.andM;A $595 fiber-optic transceiver also joins the LinkBuilder family.andM;The 10 new products are scheduled for release in mid-December.andP;  They will besold through 3Com's normal distribution channels.andP;  Future LinkBuilderadditions will include bridges, routers and integrated protocol processors.andO;3Com can be reached at (800) 638-3266.andO;</TEXT></DOC>